<TEXT>
panama will boycott a panama canal 
commission meeting because the united states invited an ambassador 
loyal to ousted president eric arturo delvalle and denied entry 
visas for two delegates an official said 
oyden ortega one of four panamanian delegates to the 
commission told a news conference monday the united states had 
invited juan b sosa whom it recognizes as panamas ambassador to 
washington to attend the oct 1213 meeting in new orleans 
he said sosas presence introduces an element of politics into 
the canal commission meetings and an institutional meeting would 
have been preferable 
ortega said panama would send a document to us commission 
members stating that its decision to boycott the meeting did not 
affect panamas compliance with the 1977 panama canal treaties 
the commission oversees administration of the canal until dec 
31 1999 when panama is to assume full responsibility for the 
waterway that connects the atlantic and pacific oceans 
sosa served as panamas envoy under delvalle who was deposed in 
february after he tried to fire gen manuel antonio noriega 
noriega panamas de facto ruler as head of the defense forces is 
under us indictment on drug trafficking charges noriega denies 
any wrongdoing 
the reagan administration continues to recognize delvalle as 
panamas legitimate president 
ortega said the united states denied a visa to maj daniel 
delgado panamas executive director for treaty affairs for what 
he called political declarations against the united states 
delegate arnulfo suarez also was denied a us visa but ortega 
declined to say why 
in july panama ordered its commission representatives not to 
attend a scheduled meeting in savannah ga because of us 
sanctions against noriega 
in the panamanians absence the five american members voted to 
suspend commission regulations calling for at least two of its four 
annual meetings to be held in panama 
</TEXT>
