<TEXT>
broadcasters and freespeech defenders say a 
new law that will ban indecent material from radio and 
television is unconstitutional and they are preparing to challenge 
the measure in court 
congress passed the blanket prohibition because of complaints by 
some lawmakers that the federal communications commission was 
allowing the airwaves to be sullied with smut 
the fact that this is an election year however did not go 
unnoticed others in congress say 
its an electionyear fear said rep neal smith diowa 
who argued on the house floor that a ban would be found 
unconstitutional it was just a fear that someone might think 
they were for pornography or obscenity 
obscenity is banned on radio and tv at all times but the fcc 
allows a category of less offensive material termed indecent 
to be broadcast when children are unlikely to be listening or 
watching 
were not talking about obscenity but material that has a lot 
of societal value artistic literary even political merit and 
because the definition is so broad it could be considered 
indecent said timothy b dyk a lawyer representing 
freedomofspeech advocates 
the fcc had set midnight to 6 am as a safe harbor for the 
socalled indecent material but a federal appeals court in 
washington last summer said the commission failed to make a case 
for those hours and ordered a review 
the new law appears to make that review moot now the fcc must 
come up with a new set of rules to ban indecency by jan 31 1989 
overtheair broadcasts but not cable programming would be 
covered 
representatives of broadcasting companies first amendment 
advocates and civil liberties defenders that earlier challenged the 
fccs indecency rules met recently to discuss the impending ban 
said dyk lead attorney in the appeals court case 
its safe to predict that some or all of the original group 
will challenge the new law he said 
in the earlier case decided july 29 by the us court of 
appeals for the district of columbia the court makes plain that 
banning indecent material during the entire 24hour period is 
plainly unconstitutional dyk said 
the senate passed the ban in july after its sponsor sen jesse 
helms rnc alleged that the fcc was permitting broadcasters to 
air programs that included disgusting bestiality sodomy and 
child sex 
garbage is garbage no matter what the time of day or night may 
be helms said on the senate floor he offered no specifics 
the fcc last year lowered its window for the socalled indecent 
broadcasts moving the cutoff time from 10 pm to midnight the 
commission had refrained from an aroundtheclock ban because it 
said court rulings have held that the first amendment protects 
indecent speech allowing restrictions only to keep such material 
away from children 
peggy charren president of the cambridge massbased action 
for childrens television agreed that electionyear politics 
clearly is behind the new prohibition on indecency 
pornography is one thing nobodys for that but thats not 
what is being talked about here indecency is not child 
pornography she said 
people who worry about keeping speech away from children are 
the kind of people who burn books who reedit textbooks who want 
to torch television programs and that is never the way to deal with 
a speech problem for anybody including children she said 
charrens group was one of the many involved in the appeals 
court case decided in july two days after the senate passed its 
ban it cited a 1978 supreme court ruling in reaffirming that 
indecent speech is protected by the first amendment 
it also upheld the fccs definition of indecency as material 
that depicts or describes in terms patently offensive as 
measured by contemporary community standards for the broadcast 
medium sexual or excretory activities or organs 
even some at the fcc are concerned about the constitutionality 
of the new ban but fcc commissioner james h quello said its 
law and we have to enforce it 
im for everything we can do to curb obscenity but this might 
be going farther than the constitution intended he said 
</TEXT>
