<TEXT>
federal officials have proposed 80 steps to 
improve operations at the nations busiest airport including 
incentives to attract experienced airtraffic controllers 
according to a report published today 
the recommendations for chicagos ohare international airport 
came in a federal aviation administration study that has not yet 
been officially released the new york times said 
the study preceded last weeks faa move to restrict ohare 
flights during peak traffic hours in response to recent controller 
errors the times said 
the study proposed higher pay and other incentives for 
controllers and recommended lightening controllers workloads by 
alleviating radio congestion and easing restrictions on the use of 
intersecting runways when they are wet from rain said the times 
todays turbojet aircraft are capable of operating safely on 
such runways in the right conditions the report said 
it further suggested locating deicing stations near where 
planes take off to ease congestion caused when aircraft must return 
to boarding gates for a second deicing after waiting too long in 
the snow 
the proposals would need approval at higher levels of the reagan 
administration before they could be enacted and some would require 
congressional legislation 
there have been 30 controller flighthandling errors so far this 
year in the chicago area which includes ohare and numerous 
satellite airfields compared to 12 during all of last year 
officials said 
the faa study was ordered aug 8 the day the national 
transportation safety board sent the agency 11 recommendations for 
safer handling of flights in the chicago area 
that list also included incentives to attract top controllers 
and suggested using simulators in their training the boards 
recommendations were prompted by earlier controller errors 
