<TEXT>
federal undercover agents lured nine people 
to a fake wedding and then arrested them in connection with an 
international moneylaundering scheme a newspaper reported today 
the us attorneys office has scheduled a news conference today 
to discuss the case and announce the indictments handed up earlier 
this month according to unidentified sources cited by the tampa 
tribune 
top drug enforcement officials from britain and france have 
investigated the case a reputed 40 million moneylaundering 
operation in cooperation with us agents the newspaper said 
the nine people arrested sunday were invited to the wedding by a 
us customs agent playing the role of a drug financier seeking 
advice on money laundering the newspaper said 
it was a cecil b demille production the unidentified 
federal official said of the fictitious wedding 
five of the nine are past or present employees of the 
multinational bank of credit and commerce international said bank 
attorney marty steinberg in miami 
we havent been provided with any specific allegations were 
anxiously waiting to see what the charges are said steinberg 
iqbal ashraf a pakistaniborn british citizen opened the tampa 
branch of the bank in late 1984 
the banks major business was providing letters of credit and 
helping finance international business deals he said 
ashraf said the bank was founded in the early 1970s and is owned 
by a holding company in luxembourg 
federal officials declined to comment on the case monday 
the nine people arrested sunday were being held in the 
hillsborough county jail without bail 
