<TEXT>
the supreme court today barred a missouri 
couple whose child has downs syndrome from suing their doctor for 
failing to tell them a test would have revealed the disorder prior 
to birth 
the court without comment refused to review a wrongful 
birth claim by parents who said they would have chosen abortion 
if they knew the child had the disorder 
carl and barbara wilson sued dr donald kuenzi of gladstone mo 
mrs wilson was 36 at the time she conceived and 37 when she 
gave birth to her son robert on june 23 1983 
robert was born with downs syndrome a genetic disorder that 
causes mental retardation and other defects 
the wilsons cited medical evidence that the risk of a child 
having the disorder is about one in 1000 when the mother is in her 
20s and about one in 300 when she is 36 
the wilsons said kuenzi failed to inform them the disorder can 
be detected by a test known as amniocentesis in which fluid is 
removed from the womb with a needle inserted through the stomach 
the wilsons sued the doctor for negligence on their own behalf 
a wrongful birth claim and on their sons behalf a wrongful life 
claim 
missouri enacted a law in 1986 which bars such suits 
the missouri supreme court ruled last april that the law could 
not be applied retroactively to block the wilsons suit 
but the state court dismissed the suit anyway ruling that 
permitting such suits conflicts with the states policy on personal 
injury claims or torts 
a finding that we will not create and will not recognize 
either a new tort for wrongful life or for wrongful birth is in our 
opinion totally compatible with the policy considerations expressed 
by our legislature in attempting to limit the statute of 
limitations for malpractice actions the state court said 
in the wrongfulbirth action the right to recovery is based 
solely on the woman testifying long after the fact and when it is 
in her financial interest to do so that she would have chosen to 
abort if the physician had but told her of the amniocentesis 
test the state court said it would seem that testimony either 
more verifiable based upon experience or more verifiable by some 
objective standard should be required as the basis for any action 
for substantial damages 
in the appeal acted on today the wilsons said that barring the 
suit violated their constitutional rights the state court did not 
address that question specifically 
the state court did note that wrongfulbirth suits have been 
permitted in some states but the missouri court said those states 
have had trouble explaining how a genetic disorder is the result of 
any injury negligently inflicted by the doctor 
the wilsons said shielding doctors from such suits restricts 
freedom of choice for women by allowing physicians who oppose 
abortion for moral or religious reasons to withhold vital 
information from the mother 
the case is wilson vs kuenzi 88362 
