<TEXT>
a us navy chemist has found a way to convert 
sewer gas into diamonds 
dr james e butler tapped washingtons sewage system for the 
methane gas he used to grow diamond crystals at the naval research 
laboratory other chemists at the lab have grown diamond crystals 
by using an oxygenacetylene torch butler said in a telephone 
interview tuesday 
the tiny diamonds made in his process using chemical vapors to 
deposit crystals on a surface could have a variety of industrial 
applications including abrasives protective coatings and 
computer insulators he said 
but i dont think well be able to grow diamonds of gemstone 
size and quality in the near future butler said 
the navy scientists are working on a process that entails 
heating chemical vapors under normal air pressure or less and 
getting carbon from the vapor to crystallize on a surface at 
temperatures of about 1440 degrees fahrenheit 
current industrial processes for making diamonds require much 
higher heat and pressure 
why use sewer gas 
sewer gas was just a case of having a convenient inexpensive 
source of methane butler said the naval research laboratory is 
next door to washingtons blue plains waste water treatment plant 
methane a combination of carbon and hydrogen is a primary 
constituent of sewer gas it is generally burned as waste 
researchers in other countries have performed some similar 
experiments butler said commenting that such sources of carbon as 
vodka have also been used 
it will be years before the diamondmaking system could be 
developed into an industrial scale he said but when that happens 
plenty of raw material will be available 
</TEXT>
