<TEXT>
several thousand university of maryland 
students are being tested for aids in what researchers say is the 
first voluntary study to determine how widespread the disease is on 
a college campus 
the universitys college park campus was selected because with 
38000 students it is one of the nations most populated campuses 
enrolls a heterogeneous group of students and is in the 
washingtonbaltimore area where the aids virus is more prevalent 
than is typical nationwide researchers said 
the study is sponsored by the university of marylands medical 
school in baltimore and the national institute for allergy and 
infectious diseases in bethesda 
we wont be able to say where the infection was obtained but 
well be able to assess the rate said the studys director dr 
karen kotloff an assistant professor of pediatric infectious 
diseases at the university of maryland at baltimore 
this is one very unique population we are monitoring a large 
somewhat contained population with a high level of sexual 
activity kotloff said tuesday 
kotloff said she did not expect the rate of positive test 
results for the aids antibody to be as high among college students 
as among military recruits an equivalent age group tests of 
military recruits found 16 out of every 1000 tested positive for 
the hiv virus 
about 200 students were tested monday the day the study began 
kotloff said researchers hope to draw blood from 6000 students 
through nov 30 
students in late adolescence and their early 20s simply dont 
perceive themselves as being at risk because they identify 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome as a disease that primarily 
strikes homosexual men and intravenous drug users said stan 
kinder assistant director of the university health center 
students who participated expressed hope the study would 
increase awareness 
i think its really good theyre doing it because maybe it 
will make people more aware you cant just jump in anybodys bed 
and cavort around said tanya mattocks a sophomore the 
disease is there you cant just say i wont get it 
senior tom fennelly called the study a good way for students 
who are shy about it to find out confidentially if they have the 
virus 
the federal centers for disease control in atlanta is also 
sponsoring a study involving 20 campuses nationwide including 
college park each campus is being asked to provide samples of 
blood from 1000 students 
kotloff said the new study differs significantly from the cdcs 
the cdc study is an anonymous test of the blood of students who 
come into campus health clinics for other reasons and gave a blood 
sample while they are there 
the college park study uses volunteers who are asked to complete 
a questionnaire about their sexual practices along with basic 
information such as age race sex and residence students are 
counseled about the implications of the test results before 
donating blood kotloff said 
participants will be able to find out the result of their tests 
which will remain confidential officials said 
kotloff said her study will also test an additional 2000 blood 
samples obtained anonymously to use as a check of the voluntary 
study 
