<TEXT>
residents will decide next month whether a 
proposal to permit predominantly black boston neighborhoods to 
become a separate new city named mandela amounts to segregation or 
good civic sense 
the nonbinding referendum on the ballot nov 8 is similar to 
one soundly defeated in 1986 by a 31 margin those results were 
far better than the 91 margin of defeat predicted and backers who 
say the change would improve municipal services said they were 
encouraged to try again 
if the reaction had been a big yawn then we probably wouldnt 
be doing this right now said state rep byron rushing a boston 
democrat 
but this time there is little of the excitement created two 
years ago the movement that inspired its own rap song in 1986 
hasnt even drawn formal opposition this time 
the rev charles r stith a prominent black leader and a chief 
opponent said the proposed city of mandela named after jailed 
black south african nationalist nelson mandela could not survive 
without the citywide tax base of boston 
mayor raymond flynn opposes the referendum because it would 
segregate the community said his press secretary arthur jones 
and if the measure were approved it would have to be signed by 
gov michael s dukakis who also is against it 
the proposed city of about 125000 people would include a 
12squaremile area made up of all of roxbury and parts of the 
dorchester mattapan and jamaica plain sections of the city boston 
covers 427 square miles and has 570000 residents 
supporters argue the areas have long been neglected and would 
fare better with control of their own tax dollars 
the secession drive stemmed from a feeling that city leaders had 
run out of options for improving municipal services such as police 
