philippine and us officials have 
tentatively agreed that washington will pay more than 550 million 
annual compensation to use its military bases in the phillipines 
official sources said tuesday 
the sources who spoke on condition of anonymity said an accord 
on terms to cover the us lease through 1991 is expected within a 
week 
in washington state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said 
there was no agreement assistant secretary of state gaston sigur 
and philippines foreign secretary raul manglapus discussed the 
subject there tuesday 
the philippine sources said negotiators agreed on a basic annual 
package of 550 million to 580 million in economic support 
military aid and commodities mostly wheat for the united states 
continued use of the six bases through 1991 
us and filipino panels began reviewing the 1947 agreement on 
the base leases in april but talks stalled over compensation and 
other issues 
the united states has been paying about 180 million a year 
under the current agreement but filipino officials reportedly want 
that increased to 12 billion for the last two years of the lease 
the facilities include clark air base and subic bay naval base and 
comprise the largest us garrison in southeast asia 
any extension on the lease past 1991 must be approved by 
twothirds of the 23member senate where opposition to the us 
presence is strong mrs aquino who holds office until 1992 has 
refused to say where she stands on the issue 
opponents of the bases say they infringe on philippine 
sovereignty and pose dangers to the country in the event of 
superpower conflicts 
sources close to the talks said the filipino negotiators in 
washington were bargaining for an additional loan of 100 million 
to purchase us treasury bonds which would be used to help pay 
the philippines 28 billion foreign debt 
teodoro benigno the spokesman for president corazon aquino 
told reporters the size of the compensation package had not yet 
been agreed upon he said the 550 million figure was a hard cash 
component and officials were still discussing creative 
portions meaning the debt relief part 
in congress rep renato unico told reporters that us 
ambassador nicholas platt who heads the american negotiating 
panel met him and another proadministration congressman at lunch 
tuesday 
he quoted platt as saying that the americans were offering 481 
million a year through 1991 and that us officials believe most 
filipinos will opt for the retention of the bases when the lease 
expires 
it was not clear if the figure platt mentioned was offered 
before manglapus went to washington 
