<TEXT>
the energy department has admitted hundreds of 
eastern bloc and other foreign visitors into its nuclear weapons 
labs without required security checks a senate hearing was told 
tuesday 
the visitors included suspected foreign agents and people from 
overseas facilities believed to be trying to build nuclear weapons 
according to keith fultz of the congressional general accounting 
office 
fultz who did not identify any of these people told 
governmental affairs committee chairman john glenn dohio that 
gao does not believe the three highlevel research labs are fully 
protected against espionage 
the visitors mainly scientists came from a variety of 
communist bloc nations headed by the soviet union and china and 
nuclearsensitive nations like israel india south africa 
pakistan iran and iraq he said 
we could not determine if sensitive or classified information 
has been lost but because of weaknesses in does foreign 
visitor controls we have little confidence that adequate 
protection of weaponsrelated information and technology is 
achieved fultz said 
he said that even if no supersecret data were available the 
situation threatens us interests 
doe studies have concluded that unclassified information at 
the laboratories may provide foreign countries details on sensitive 
and even classified activities that the united states 
conducts fultz said 
richard du val a deputy assistant energy secretary said 
officials began tightening security a year ago but he could not 
assure chairman glenn that no foreign visitor was getting into the 
labs now without proper screening 
fultz detailed the results of a gao study of foreigners who 
between january 1986 and september 1987 visited los alamos and 
sandia labs in new mexico and californias lawrence livermore lab 
which is doing work on the strategic defense initiative sometimes 
called the star wars program 
energy department security procedures require a background check 
in most cases before a lab admits someone from a communist or 
nuclearsensitive nation 
fultz said a review of the files on 181 communistbloc visitors 
showed that 176 should have been checked out with the fbi and 
intelligence agencies no checks were done for 119 and only 7 
checks were completed before a visit began 
doe obtained even less background information on visitors from 
other sensitive countries said fultz 637 visitors 77 
background checks only 14 completed before the visitor arrived 
he said that no checks were done on the approximately 10 percent 
of the these visitors who are affiliated with organizations on the 
departments watch list because of suspected nuclear weapons 
activities 
fultz quoted department officials as saying that only one of the 
818 visits broached a sensitive topic we found at least 37 
others related to inertial confinement fusion and isotope 
separation which are identified as sensitive by doe 
energy officials say their basic line of defense is security 
plans tailored to specific visitors and setting parameters for what 
can be discussed and what areas of a lab can be visited 
fultz said the labs prepared such plans in only 89 of the 248 
visits that fell under this requirement 
he said that there are problems even when the department knows 
about visitors in advance 
the energy field office in san francisco tried to limit a soviet 
officials visit to livermore to public access areas but lab 
officials allowed the official to spend a significant part of 
this visit in classified areas according to fultz 
and in a recent case the department officials in washington 
denied two israelis access to an unidentified lab one of them got 
a lab employee to tap into the labs unclassified computer from a 
terminal in the employees garage according to du val 
im not aware of any other cases like this but i wouldnt bet 
on it du val said its no longer a matter of whether the 
visitors are inside the fence 
