<TEXT>
us authorities may offer ferdinand marcos a 
promise he will not go to prison if he pleads guilty and forfeits 
money he allegedly stole from the philippine treasury when he was 
that countrys president government sources said tuesday 
the possibility of making the offer to marcos who has not been 
indicted was discussed last week at a meeting between the state 
departments chief legal counsel abraham sofaer and an aide to 
attorney general dick thornburgh said the sources speaking on 
condition of anonymity 
the sources supplied the information following a story in the 
los angeles times which had obtained a state department cable 
relayed from sofaer to other department officials following last 
weeks meeting between sofaer and thornburgh aide robin ross 
the discussions between the state and justice departments 
revolve around a criminal investigation of marcos by us attorney 
rudolph giuliani in manhattan 
the white house said the national security council staff has 
informally reviewed information from the justice department 
outlining a proposed fraud case against marcos 
but white house spokesman marlin fitzwater said tuesday that the 
matter hasnt come to the president yet 
the justice department is considering whether to bring it 
before a grand jury fitzwater said they have given us 
information on the case 
fitzwater said the matter would be presented to reagan for a 
decision after a formal recommendation has been received from 
thornburgh recommendations also will be sought from secretary of 
state george shultz and others in the cabinet he said 
asked if a decision from reagan can be expected before the nov 
8 presidential election fitzwater said i have no idea the 
justice department has given us a preliminary indication of the 
basis of the case 
according to the cable obtained by the times the state 
department wants to give marcos a last chance prior to 
indictment to reach a settlement federal prosecutors prefer to 
indict him first to gain added leverage 
the department of justice has presented no good reason why 
we should not continue to insist on offering mr marcos a chance to 
reach a voluntary plea agreement prior to indictment the cable 
said 
the cable also said federal officials fear that marcos if 
indicted might seek to involve and embarrass us and 
philippine officials by making allegations of improper or illegal 
conduct by them 
the times quoted unidentified sources familiar with the 
investigation as saying us officials are worried that marcos may 
threaten to reveal politically damaging information about his 
dealings with us officials to pressure the white house to block 
prosecution 
the state department also had argued that any indictment of 
marcos should be limited to alleged criminal acts committed after 
he fled to hawaii 
prosecutors in giulianis office have countered that the only 
way to recover any of the allegedly illgotten fortune in manhattan 
real estate and fine art that marcos allegedly has acquired is to 
charge him with acts of fraud that began while he was still 
president of the philippines 
state department officials according to the cable finally 
accepted the prosecutors argument on condition that the indictment 
be drawn and that thornburghs public statements be constructed 
to emphasize illegal conduct after marcos came to the united states 
the cable said its is important to offer marcos a plea bargain 
even if he declines to accept it 
prosecution of mr marcos could set a precedent that would 
have a negative impact on our ability to influence other heads of 
state who may be similarly situated to leave power the cable 
said 
