<TEXT>
diplomats were deadlocked over the weekend in 
trying to set a timetable for pulling out 50000 cuban troops from 
angola cuban and angolan envoys involved in the negotiations said 
tuesday 
south africa has scheduled for nov 1 the start of an 
independence plan for neighboring southwest africa known as 
namibia but it has linked it to cuban troop withdrawal from angola 
the pretoria government says the cubans threaten the 
independence of namibia which borders angola 
cubas deputy foreign minister ricardo alarcon de quesada and 
angolas ambassador to the un manuel pedro pacavira said the 
us cuban angolan and south african negotiators reached no 
agreement in talks held friday through sunday 
they spoke at a news conference in response to published reports 
saying the talks reached agreement on a 24to30 month pullout by 
the cubans 
we are at an impasse which is not precisely synonymous with 
agreement said alarcon 
as you can see in the newspapers reports almost daily we 
havent yet achieved an agreement or understanding on the calendar 
for the withdrawal of the cuban forces in angola he said 
pacavira reiterated that assessment during the news conference 
held at the national council of churches headquarters in manhattan 
alarcon said cuba and angola need 30 months to train and equip 
angolan forces to deal with any future raids by south africa or by 
the unita rebels that are backed by the united states and south 
africa 
the united states serving as mediator in the talks has 
suggested a 24month withdrawal and south africa agrees said 
alarcon and pacavira 
pacavira said the conflicting proposals were advanced a month 
ago in a meeting in brazzaville congo 
south africa in the past has launched periodic raids from 
namibia into southern angola to back up unita forces when they 
encountered heavy resistance from cuban forces 
under a preliminary agreement in the peace talks all south 
african forces left southern angola by sept 1 
president pw botha of south africa on tuesday termed reports 
of an agreement inaccurate saying the timetable needs to be 
worked out he commented while on a visit to zurich switzerland 
in washington state department spokeswoman phyllis oakley said 
the talks were helpful in more precisely defining the gaps 
remaining between the parties 
they recognize that further decisions are required to reach an 
agreement acceptable to all sides she said 
diplomats involved in the talks say they are working toward 
reaching agreement on a cuban withdrawal timetable at a meeting to 
be held this month in brazzaville 
however us officials botha and alarcon have said it may not 
be possible to reach the nov 1 deadline set by the united nations 
for transition to independence for namibia 
when the independence plan begins the united nations will send 
7500 peacekeepers and 2000 civilian support staff to supervise 
elections for a national assembly that will adopt a constitution 
and form an independent government 
under the un plan independence will be achieved in one year 
as the un peacekeepers maintain order and supervise the south 
african withdrawal 
