congress on tuesday completed final action on 
a bill to extend and tighten controls on clinical laboratories to 
make sure they are doing accurate and reliable testing work 
the senate approved the bill on a voice vote sending the 
measure to president reagan for his signature the house passed it 
last week 
rep john dingell dmich chairman of the house energy and 
commerce committee said the new law will set standards for 
virtually all labs and give the department of health and human 
services new enforcement tools 
the bill was prompted by reports of problems sometimes 
lifethreatening at unregulated labs doing shoddy work sponsors 
were particularly concerned about labs in doctors offices which 
had been exempt from existing federal regulation 
dingell said the new law will set strict standards for pap 
smears require dissemination of information on lab performance 
and set new civil and criminal penalties for labs that violate 
regulations a new and tougher method of evaluating lab performance 
would be instituted 
the bill also would strengthen federal oversight of the 
professional organizations that have been largely responsible for 
monitoring lab performance 
some flexibility would be given to labs that only perform tests 
in which erroneous results would not pose a significant risk to 
patients 
pap test regulations would include workload limits for those 
reading the slides improperly collected specimens would be 
returned to doctors and slides of women in highrisk groups would 
be rescreened before a diagnosis was made 
