<TEXT>
argonne national laboratory has sold a process 
that could dramatically reduce pollution from coalfire power 
plants to a pennsylvania company lab officials said tuesday 
the buyer dravo lime co of pittsburgh which makes chemicals 
for smokestack scrubbers is betting that tighter acidrain 
controls will make the deal a profitable one 
officials say the process can be used with existing equipment to 
reduce by 70 percent a plants output of nitrogen oxide believed 
along with sulfur oxides to be a major cause of acid rain 
the driving force on all this is the potential of new 
legislation on acid rain said david livengood an argonne 
researcher who managed the project 
acid rain formed when the sulfur and nitrogen gases combine 
with the air to form acids is believed to cause widespread damage 
to forests and lakes 
the new process called argonox involves spraying water mixed 
with substances called metal chelates into a chamber through 
which coal smoke must pass the metal chelates then combine with 
nitrogen to form a solid substance that can be removed from the 
chamber and hauled away 
dravo says the new technology will pay for itself because power 
plants seeking to comply with tougher acidrain laws will prefer 
the argonox system which can be fitted to existing scrubbers to 
other methods requiring costly equipment changes 
scrubbers which use lime to remove sulfur oxides from coal 
smoke have been installed at many power plants and other 
industries 
dravo spokesman ron sommer said the company expected to have a 
pilot project installed at the miami fort power plant near 
cincinnati sometime in the next year 
dravo bought the process from argonne a department of energy 
lab in suburban lemont operated by the university of chicago as 
part of a program encouraging the sale of the fruits of government 
research to private industry 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

